Ukraine on the path to Europe
"The East is the East, and the West is the West, and the two will never meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
Ukraine is undoubtedly in the east, but in the east of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the overriding goal for many of us.
The path there, however, was not always paved with success, if it was paved at all.
However, the result of the parliamentary elections on 31 March has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go this way.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It's beyond question for me that our "Soviet" heritage is to a large extent responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in finding its way to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country possessed an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural farming areas were effectively paralyzed by outdated machinery parks and the lethargy of the state-led agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, the pensions are a joke, and the black market is huge.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We have completely messed up the reform on our own.
Because often we wanted to import tried and tested concepts from the West - private property, a free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy - in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic undertones in politics, the Verkhovna Rada (the parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted citizens' rights and criminal law, land-, family and economic rights, which is something akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that was disconnected from European history for centuries was painful at times, but has picked up momentum, even though we don't necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as more open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also more chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Despite this, we are Europeans.
You see that on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, drivers are letting pedestrians cross the road, as in Geneva or Munich, (while pedestrians still have to get out of the way of ruthless drivers in Moscow).
In Kiev there is now a thriving café scene and friendly public spaces where people can stop and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German and French, they can handle computers and surf in the net at the Internet cafes.
But these are just the fanciful digressions of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The unemotional gaze of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper-reaching changes.
Over the past ten years, there has been a development from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted, corruptly motivated reforms to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform illustrates this very clearly.
Initially, the reform of the state evoked a hostile mood both among bureaucrats and among ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a reform "according to pattern F": the state had to shrink, so it was thought, and then the government would run smoothly.
Nobody thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive despite having large state apparatuses.
For the problem is not only one of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily improve by simply striking the red pen led us to the second stage of our reform process.
The state was gradually reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
They established new departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility.
This was stabilization of the work of the government ministries.
At the start, the authority transferred to these new areas was somewhat excessive, to arrange their work more effectively.
They work more or less normally now.
Ukrainians may sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (if reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists – of whom there are still too many among us – can afford to adopt a indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
The Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the main one, but indeed a province.
That has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny this have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial person can in no case admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe".
Since 1991, Ukrainians had to acknowledge that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming sicker ourselves, but the recent elections that brought the Communists to the forefront in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" under President Kuchma have pushed our provincial radicals to the fringes of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the periphery of Europe, we want to establish a society in which there are no outsiders or peripherals.
As the great and at the time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long and arduous path to Europe has helped a weak new nation to grow strong and survive.
